segments.text: And he helped me a lot in my work later on all these conferences that we had.
He would work the hours that it took to get the job done.
He worked many, many hours.
He was very devoted.
When you came, describe the administration of the campus at that point.
Who were they and what were their responsibilities?
Well, we had a dean of the College of Agriculture, of Engineering.
We had an arts and sciences dean.
We had medicine, vet medicine, and I, let's see, and the business administration was still a section.
Who was there, who was the president then, when you arrived?
When I arrived, I, there were two or three
Well, let's turn it around.
The basic division was, and let's work it out, basic division was headed by whom?
Oh, it was headed by John Arbitran.
John Arbitran was an A&M graduate, did his Ph.D. at Syracuse.
No, not Syracuse.
What is the... Oh, it set my mind.
But he had done his PhD at this school.
Cliff Randstolt was the assistant dean of the basic division.
And I remember in numbers,
The student body was very close to what it was in 39.
And all freshmen were in the basic division?
Yes.
Regardless of their major?
Yes.
Bertrand reported to whom?
He reported directly to the president.
To the president.
and you all were responsible for what?
Tell me about what the Basic Division did.
Well, the Basic Division was an organization of faculty members that would be responsible for the academic progress of the student
through the sophomore year, if necessary.
The students would all be under the same academic dean, which was Dean Bertrand.
We had a staff of about six or seven counselors, and these counselors filled many roles.
They did all of the testing and placement
They worked with the day-to-day problems of the students.
We taught what was called basic courses, which were guidance courses.
Study skills, vocational guidance, things of this type.
And this was available to the veteran, too.
I remember, and we had
We had some courses which were taught for the purpose of trying to get the student like chemistry 100.
This would be a semester.
English 100.
Math 100.
Now this did not last too many years, but it was a reality factor.
And I saw students who had forgotten their math and they would take math 100 and the first thing you know they were doing as well as the others.
It was not a goofball type thing.
Where were y'all physically located?
We were in the old Aggieland Inn.
Cross from Sabeasa.
Cross from Sabeasa.
And we had, we used two floors of that thing.
We, there was a young couple who were there to, they were there simply to keep an eye on the rest of the Aggieland Inn because the MSC had
had kind of taken over that part of it.
Now, it had once been a hotel, small hotel, motel, life facility.
When the MSC opened, did it continue to have overnight gas?
It did overflow.
But we...
I think it was my second year that it was turned completely over to us.
Well, we thought we'd blocked off the floors, but we later found the old boy had been camping out up there.
Now, the staff that we had
would serve as strong supporters of youngsters who were having difficulty of any type.
We were given a lot of latitude in which to work.
If we felt that the student was in a course that it was completely impossible, we could no-grade drop it.
Or we could work with the department to work out some solution to it.
There was a lot of flexibility in the way that it was carried out.
Were there, in those years, some assistant and associate deans in each of the colleges with whom y'all had close working relationships?
They had similar responsibilities?
I don't think so.
I think that there were associate deans like Mickey McGuire and, of course, Cliff over there later when the thing worked a different way.
But you all were the primary academic counselors, advisors on the campus.
Yes.
Share with this machine and the future
some anecdotes, some stories that give examples of some of the variety of experiences that you had.
Well, you know, it was sort of practical.
I remember the first year that I was, I had gone to the A&M adjunct in July and talked out there
for six weeks, and then I came back to the campus.
I had this student come in one morning, and he was very distraught, he was very upset.
And he said, I have slept through
my quiz A in chemistry.
And he said, the whole thing is going to blow because I've got to make it.
And I said, well, why did you choose to?
He said, well, I work.
And when I came in, I was so tired that I forgot to set the alarm.
So I did it.
Well, I wrote a note to the professor of chemistry and said, I think this is a very fine young man, and I think he's sincere, and I would appreciate it if we could work something out.
Well, the prof felt the same way, but he's glad to get a fancy to
They say, well, I did because Curtis told me.
Well, the interesting thing is that that young man later became a state chemist at Texas A&M University.
How nice.
And he has retired now out from Blanco and a very fine man.
But it was...
But it was disappointing in a way though.
My personal opinion is that we were getting the students that were in school during the war years in the public school and they probably
lack of discipline.
I mean, knowing and staying with something.
And we simply were getting a number of those.
We also taught a course in vocational guidance.
And the purpose was to try to get the student into the right field.
Not necessarily the course, but into the right field.
And I sometimes wonder if we're any better off now than we were then.
That's a tantalizing problem that I worked with for 30 years.
And I think we've made progress.
But it's a shame, Pastor, for a young person to dump
and spend the money that it takes.
And then you discover that they really have no characteristics or strength to be doing that.
What about some memories of some students that gave you a song and dance story that made up something which you had reason to believe might have been fabricated?
One of the most interesting things that happened was that at the end of the semester, we always went through this ritual of the students would be dropped.
That was one of the things that kind of broke our back, I think, was that we didn't give much understanding.
we would, Dr. Ransdell and I would take the appeals.
Well this student came in to me and I always prefaced a few comments by saying that
We're here to help you.
It's not punishment, but it's what is best for you and for the college.
So now tell me in your own language why you feel that we should continue you.
He said, alright.
He said, I can do that.
He said, you know, I have been down in the chapel all morning.
And he said, I prayed.
And God has called me to stay here and minister to the Aggies.
And I thought, uh-oh.
I
I did a sneaky thing, I guess.
I said, well, I believe this is beyond me.
I'm going to ask you to wait outside and see Dr.
Ransom.
And I would never let someone stay without clearing the cliff because he was carrying a burden.
Well, you know, there was a saying that if you can stay in Dr. Ransel's office 30 minutes, you can stay in school.
Oh, really?
Oh, no, I hadn't heard that.
Yeah, well, that's what the kids... Well, the Corps had some very implicit comments to make about professors.
Very meaningful something that...
and they share it with their students.
Well, I don't know how it worked out later, but I will say a follow up on this.
I had a minister in graduate class.
And he and I were visiting during the break.
We had class from 5 to 8.
I said, you know, I want to tell you something, and I want to ask you what would you have done?
So I told him this story.
And he said, Mr. Curtis, I can help you.
He said, I had something happen one time that's a good example.
He said, it's a cold Sunday winter evening, and I had gone to the chapel.
to open it up for any of the GIs that wanted to come.
And he said, I opened it up, and I went off to do something, came back, and there was this soldier sitting down on the front row.
So I went over and said, soldier, can I help you?
He said, I don't know whether you can or not, but he said, I've been called to preach here tonight.
And I said, boy, you're getting close.
And he said, well, I talked to him a little bit, and he said, the boy insisted that this was the chapel that he had been called.
And the fellow said, well, he said, now, soldier, he said, I believe that God has called you to preach.
And he may have called you to preach in a chapel, but that would be between you and God.
But he said, if God had wanted you to preach here tonight, he would have told me so I could have made better preparation.
He said, frankly, I think you're in the wrong chapel.
So the GI sat there for a little while, he said, and got up and left.
He said, I don't know whether he found the right chapel or not.
It was a hard effort to try to show that we had concern.

Now, but we had helpers, so to speak, out in the faculty because we not only would have this help in a staff type thing, but each one of these freshmen had an advisor in the area in which he was hoping to major.
This was a volunteer professor.
Right, and a freshman entered, was assigned to the basic division, and to leave the basic division had to have how many hours and what kind of grades?
He had to have 30 hours and 30 grade points.
Okay, and then could enter whatever major.
Yes, yes.
And that program lasted until about when, the basic division?
It lasted through 59.
And on September the 1st, 1960, then the academic supervision went to the college concerned.
And then a counseling and testing center was established.
And I was made director of it.
Now who, as far as you know, who were the primary people who...
were responsible for those changes?
I think it came out of the concern.
I don't think this was an ugly thing at all.
I think the concern was that here we are in this college and we have little or no control over the entering students and this sort of thing.
We believe that we could at least do as well as the people that are doing it.
They said, we are not trying to take over the guidance function.
That's the last thing we want.
And so Dean Huber gumshoed this.
He, for President Rudder, he was the one that
did the organizing, and he had a lot to do with it.
But he established a committee that was made up of, frankly, the professors that would be handling this in agriculture, all of these colleges.
And we worked all morning, once a week, all during the spring semester of 59, getting ready for the transition.
All right.
What were your first impressions of this new president named Earl Runner?
Well, my impression was that here's a person who knows where they're going.
And they are going to be fair, but they have high standards.
Did you all have the impression that he was sent here, he was selected for some kind of particular function, reason, purpose?
No, I don't think so.
Because, frankly...
he came after we were going as a counseling center.
But our feeling was that he supported a counseling center, but he had very high standards.
And Frank Hubert, your first impressions of him?
Oh, well, Dean Hubert has always impressed me as an excellent leader.
He's careful.
I know because all during those months in 59, well, he would have me over one morning a week, and my job was to give him complete orientation
to a counseling center and what all can be done.
And this was over in his office in Nagle Hall.

Because during that first year, I, as a beginning faculty member, being able to be here only because a faculty member named John Hill was on leave at the University of Houston, and I occupied his office, which was right next door.
And the only reason that I got a nice office.
Describe Hubert's other characteristics, sense of humor and techniques and so forth.
Well, Dean Hubert, I remember we were walking back from a meeting, Dean Hubert, Dr.
Ransom, and myself, and Cliff wanted to talk to him.
And...
We were walking along there and Dean Hubert said, now Cliff, what is this arm twisting you want to do?
What was he?
And I thought, boy, that's a pretty direct way of going about this sort of thing.
Well, I found also from, he had, he was a man of high standards.
And he told you what he needed.
And he never tried to tell you how to do it.
He just, this is what I need.
Could he get to the point rather quickly?
Yes.
Yes.
As a matter of fact, I think if he started something like that, I knew to move on.
But he was, now he is all business.
I think he's the type of person who says, when you're working, you work.

One of the little things I've been trying to discover, if possible, that I have not yet, is how Frank Hubert, then the superintendent of schools in Orange, got identified to come over here as dean of arts and sciences.
Do you have any idea...
I think I have an observation on that.
It is my understanding that President Rutter wanted to get a dean.
See, education was under him.
I wanted to get a dean that was well known in the public schools of the state.
See, we were trying to break in on this problem.
In 1960, Dean Hubert sort of ramrodded this.
But I was the one to turn the crank.
we wanted to get something out that we could send to the high schools that would give them a reason to know us and know about us.
So I suggested that we develop a counselor's handbook.
What would you want in a counselor's handbook
if you were a high school counselor to help.
So Dean Hubert approved it, said get with it.
So we first invited people in the state that were connected with education and we wanted to know us.
We had people here from the Texas Education Agency.
We chose outstanding counselors of high schools from different parts of the state.
And we had about 20 people that came to the campus.
We paid their expenses.
And we asked them to help us get the broad outline of what should be in a counselor's handbook.
This was a good meeting.
President Rutter came to the meeting.
I worked hard.
I bought some of the maroon briefcases over at the exchange store, and the girls glued the seal on the outside of it.
So when they all came in that morning at every table,
There was a nice case for them to put their things in.
We also saw that they, everywhere they went, they would take them.
I mean, it was going to meet us.
We had some head honchos out of the Texas Education Agency, and they were very helpful.
Well, for instance, this counselor down in Galveston said, I never dreamed that you had these kinds of facilities here.
So we published that counselor's handbook.
It was a real neat little handbook.
And we found out later that the University of Southern California was the only other
a university that was doing a similar thing, and we exchanged counselors' handbooks.
Well, we put out about, and by the way, the information service of the campus helped us tremendously.
There was a lady over in the agriculture, Mrs. Holland,
that helped a lot.
As a matter of fact, the second one that we put out, we profited a lot from the first.
You mean profited in experience?
Yes.
Not dollars.
No, no.
As a matter of fact, we... You gave them.
Oh yes, these were gifts that we sent to the school.
The second one went over well.
Now, I would
I would write each dean of a college and say, what would you want to be seen and read about your college in a counselor's handbook?
I remember that Dean Pearson.
Business.
Business.
Dean Pearson.
I'll always remember him as the man that would comment, we've lost the fox.
You know, we'd get to arguing and we'd get off somewhere.
Well, I sent to each associate dean and said, read this over.
Change it any way you want to.
But I want to be sure that you feel comfortable about what was written.
Business just sent theirs back.
They sent it back with no changes.
So we put it in there.
Well, when the thing was published, the colleges all got copies, and the phone rang.
And I answered it, and Dean Pearson, boy, he was pretty hot, I said.
Dean Pearson, your office approved what was written.
I have it here in the file.
He said, is that right?
I said, yes.
He said, well, I'll talk another way.
He said that the next one of these you publish, I...
I want to be sure that we do it right.
I said, well, I sure am sorry it happened too.
Now, when I was ready to publish a third one, this was about 1970, 71.
I don't know, over in the structure of the university somewhere, they established this kind of information office or something.
And so I was told to refer my plan to them.
Well, I did, and I got back a note that said, all of this is in the college catalog, and they wouldn't do it.
